- **1975:** Launch of the first “megastore” in Jakarta, featuring a dedicated **[Supply_chain](/Supply_chain)** wing that could rival the logistical nightmares of **[Corporate_finance](/Corporate_finance)** departments everywhere.  
- **1992:** Introduction of the “MPH Membership Card,” a loyalty program that managed to turn a simple transaction into an exercise in **[Consumer_behavior](/Consumer_behavior)** manipulation, complete with points that expired faster than a millennial’s attention span.  
- **2001:** Merger with a regional **[Marketing](/Marketing)** firm, resulting in a brand identity that screamed “We care about your intellectual growth” while simultaneously pushing the latest blockbuster franchise novel.  

Throughout the 2000s, MPH expanded into **[Economic_impact](/Economic_impact)** analyses, publishing glossy brochures that claimed the company contributed “significantly” to regional **[Culture](/Culture)**—a claim that, when examined under a microscope, turned out to be more about market share than genuine cultural enrichment.  

