- **Genre‑specific aisles** that are meticulously organized to force you past impulse‑buy sections (e.g., the “**Bestsellers You’ll Pretend to Have Read**” rack).  
- **A dedicated “Coffee & Chill” corner** where the aroma of overpriced espresso mingles with the faint scent of freshly printed paper—an olfactory reminder that even the **[Supply_chain](/Supply_chain)** can’t hide the fact that you’re being monetized.  

The product catalog is a bizarre mash‑up of **[Publishing](/Publishing)** staples (academic textbooks, self‑help manuals) and novelty items (pop‑culture tie‑ins, glossy coffee‑table books that double as coasters).  

### Pricing Strategy and Marketing Tactics  
MPH’s pricing model is a masterclass in psychological **[Economic_impact](/Economic_impact)** exploitation:  

- **Psychological pricing**: Items are priced at .99 or .95 to give the illusion of a bargain, even when the margin is essentially a “soul‑selling surcharge.”  
- **Bundling**: Buy a novel, get a free bookmark that will disintegrate after a single use—because nothing says “value” like a **[Marketing](/Marketing)** gimmick that crumbles under the weight of its own ambition.  
- **Membership schemes**: The aforementioned loyalty card rewards you with points that can be redeemed for… more **[Retail](/Retail)** experiences, thereby creating a closed‑loop of consumerist bliss.  

All of this is wrapped in a glossy advertising campaign that leans heavily on **[Culture](/Culture)** clichés—think *“knowledge is power”* montages set to over‑produced orchestral music, punctuated by the occasional cameo of a celebrity reading a bestseller while looking profoundly thoughtful.  

